04698nam a22005175i 9780226682518DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20191994ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266825187 a10.7208/97802266825182doi  a(DE-B1597)545031  a(OCoLC)1109725202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHM271 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a303.3/62231 aLincoln, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAuthority :bConstruction and Corrosion /cBruce Lincoln. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (235 p.) :b18 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. CONSTRUCTING AUTHORITY -- tChapter Two. ORATORY AND RIDICULE -- tChapter Three. RUMORS AND PROPHECIES -- tChapter Four. LAW, CURSES, AND DERISION -- tChapter Five. AGAINST AUTHORITY -- tChapter Six. AND WHAT ABOUT THE WOMEN? -- tChapter Seven. RELIGION AND THE CONSTRUCTION OF AUTHORITY -- tChapter Eight. SCHOLARS AND COLD WARRIORS -- tChapter Nine. PRESIDENTS AND PROTESTERS -- tAPPENDIX A. Mailing from the "Hundredth Monkey" Project -- tAPPENDIX B. Remarks by President Ronald Reagan at National Association of Broadcasters' 70th Annual Convention 13 April 1992 -- tAPPENDIX C. Interview with Rick Springer, "CBS This Morning:' 17 April 1992 -- tAPPENDIX D. "The Hundredth Monkey Speaks": An Editorial from the Wall Street Journal, 21 April 1992 -- tAPPENDIX E. "Excuse Me, Mr. President": Excerpts from an Article by Rick Springer -- tAPPENDIX F. United States vs. Springer: Excerpt from the Federal Court Record -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is authority? How is it constituted? How ought one understand the subtle (and sometimes not-so-subtle) relations between authority and coercion? Between authorized and subversive speech? In this fascinating and intricate analysis, Bruce Lincoln argues that authority is not an entity but an effect. More precisely, it is an effect that depends for its power on the combination of the right speaker, the right speech, the right staging and props, the right time and place, and an audience historically and culturally conditioned to judge what is right in all these instances and to respond with trust, respect, and even reverence. Employing a vast array of examples drawn from classical antiquity, Scandinavian law, Cold War scholarship, and American presidential politics, Lincoln offers a telling analysis of the performance of authority, and subversions of it, from ancient times to the present. Using a small set of case studies that highlight critical moments in the construction of authority, he goes on to offer a general examination of "corrosive" discourses such as gossip, rumor, and curses; the problematic situation of women, who often are barred from the authorizing sphere; the role of religion in the construction of authority; the question of whether authority in the modern and postmodern world differs from its premodern counterpart; and a critique of Hannah Arendt's claims that authority has disappeared from political life in the modern world. He does not find a diminution of authority or a fundamental change in the conditions that produce it. Rather, Lincoln finds modern authority splintered, expanded, and, in fact, multiplied as the mechanisms for its construction become more complex-and more expensive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAuthorityxHistory. 0aPolitical oratoryxHistory. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyte